Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Fill and boil your #kettle{}. Halve the @fennel{1%whole} lengthways and remove the triangular root. Slice each fennel half lengthways into four pieces. Pop them on a #baking tray{}, drizzle with @olive oil{}, and season with a pinch of @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Roast in your oven until soft, about ~{20%minutes}. Once soft, remove from your oven and set aside.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped) into small 1⁄2cm pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Zest and halve the @lemon{1%whole}(zested and halved). Finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{1%bunch}(finely chopped, stalks and all) and halve the @premium tomato mix{125%g}(halved). Roughly chop the @pine nuts{15%g}. Squeeze half the lemon juice into a #large bowl{} and add the @olive oil{1}. Add a pinch of salt and pepper, stir to combine, then add the tomatoes and leave to the side.

Put the lemon zest in a #mixing bowl{} and add a pinch of salt and pepper and the @olive oil{1%tbsp} for the fish. Stir together, then add the @sea bream fillets{2} and turn to coat in the zesty oil. Leave to the side. Heat a #saucepan{} on medium high heat and add the pine nuts (no oil). Toast them until golden, ~{2%minutes}, tossing frequently. Then remove to a #bowl{} and set aside.

Place a #large saucepan{} on medium heat with a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tbsp}. Add the onion, stir and cook until soft, ~{5%minutes}. Stir in the garlic, cook for ~{1%minute}. Add the @orzo{180%g} and @water{450%ml}, stir in the @vegetable stock powder{1%tsp} and @saffron{1%pinch}. Bring to the boil then reduce the heat and simmer uncovered until the orzo is tender, stirring every ~{2%minutes}, ~{10-12%minutes}.

> TIP: Add a splash of water if the orzo isn't tender but all the stock has been absorbed.

When the orzo is halfway through cooking, place a #frying pan{} on high heat (no oil). Once the pan is hot, lay in the bream, skin-side down and fry until the skin is golden, ~{3%minutes}, then turn and fry on the other side for ~{2%minutes}.

> The fish is cooked when opaque in the middle.

Remove the pan from the heat.

Once the orzo is cooked, remove from the heat. Stir in the @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g} and half the parsley. Taste and add a pinch of salt and pepper if you feel it needs it. Spoon into #bowls{} and top with the fish. Add the roasted fennel to the tomatoes and dressing and gently toss together. Serve on the orzo alongside the bream. Sprinkle over the pine nuts and remaining parsley. Cut the remaining lemon into wedges and serve alongside. Enjoy!